Happy Chicago Flag Day! 
The white and blue areas represent the city's physical geography. The three white bands stand for the north, west and south sides of the city, while the blue stripes are symbolic of the city's important bodies of water. The top blue band represents Lake Michigan and the north branch of the Chicago River. The first star is for Fort Dearborn, the second represents the Great Chicago Fire, the third and fourth stand for the two world's fairs that took place in Chicago.

When I give photo tips, I try to explain how I like to take a common subject area and make it more interesting. In this photo, I decided to go to the Apple store on Michigan Avenue. The wood benches there make for some great leading lines to the Apple logo if you bring your camera down to bench level. I then waited for a customer to walk directly under the Apple logo and snapped away.
Whatcha thinkin’ about? 🍎 This guy happened to stop right under the apple while he was talking on the phone. I was able to capture the moment right before he walked away.

This shot, I did with my bud Landon, was fun. We had to make it a quick one in between the car and foot traffic trying to get by, but we did it. The best part about this shot, is no one saw me shooting him from above, from the parking garage, so they just thought some random weirdo, in his suit, decided to lie in the street and grab onto the crosswalk.
